{"title_page": "Trev Thoms", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''Trevor Thoms'''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/announcements/deaths/deaths/8735913.Judge_Trev/|title=Death Notices and Obituaries: Judge Trev|last=|first=|date=14 December 2010|work=The Brighton Argus|access-date=15 August 2019}}</ref> (30 October 1950 \u2013 8 December 2010),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metal-archives.com/artists/Judge_Trev_Thoms/19263|title=Judge Trev Thoms|last=|first=|date=11 April 2011|website=Encyclopaedia Metallum - The Metal Archives|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 August 2019}}</ref> known as '''Judge Trev Thoms''' and '''Judge Trev''', was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[guitarist]], best known for being a member of [[Inner City Unit]], [[Atomgods]] and [[Steve Gibbons (musician)#Steve Gibbons Band|The Steve Gibbons Band]].\n\nIn the late 1960s and early 1970s, he played in a [[blues-rock]] group with hints of [[progressive rock]] and [[Hard rock|heavy rock]] called [[Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Iron Maiden (blues rock band)|Iron Maiden]] - not the [[Iron Maiden|famous group]] of the same name - along with Barry Skeels,<ref>Skeels, Barry (1998). Notes to CD reissue of ''Maiden Voyage''. London: Audio Archives AACD 028.</ref> who later played for Zior<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spirit-of-metal.com/groupe-groupe-Zior-l-pt.html |title=Zior - discografia, line-up, biografia, entrevistas, fotos |publisher=Spirit-of-metal.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/zior-mn0000911850 |title=Zior &#124; Discography |publisher=AllMusic |date=2005-01-04 |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref> and eventually became a [[tour manager]] for acts such as [[Black Sabbath]], [[Saxon (band)|Saxon]], [[Manowar]], and [[Yngwie Malmsteen]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livebluesworld.com/profile/BarrySkeels |title=Barry Skeels's Page |publisher=LiveBluesWorld |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref> (another member of the band was called Steve Drewett, but probably he is not the same person as the one who later founded [[The Newtown Neurotics]]).<ref>Progboard, [http://www.progboard.com/Iron-Maiden/604# Iron Maiden], Retrieved 7 July 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trouserpress.com/entry.php?a=newtown_neurotics |title=Newtown Neurotics |publisher=TrouserPress.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/steve-drewett-mn0000034324 |title=Steve Drewett &#124; Songs |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref> They recorded one album called ''Maiden Voyage''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/iron_maiden_2_/albums.jhtml?albumId=1435904 |title=Maiden Voyage by Iron Maiden |publisher=MTV |date=1969-01-01 |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/maiden-voyage-mw0000461150 |title=Maiden Voyage - Iron Maiden &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref>\n\nHe later played in the seminal British Blues Boom band, [[Spirit of John Morgan]].<ref>Brennan, Mark (1993). Notes to CD reissue of ''Spirit of John Morgan - Age Machine''. [[Repertoire Records]] REP 4354-WP.</ref> He has backed such luminaries as [[Graham Bond]], [[Gregory Isaacs]], [[Steve Gibbons (musician)|Steve Gibbons]] and was a member of [[Steve Peregrin Took]]'s  band [[Steve Took's Horns]] with [[Dino Ferari]] on [[Drum kit|drums]].<ref>Steve Peregrin Took's Domain, [http://www.stevetook.mercurymoon.co.uk/horns.html Steve Took's Horns], Retrieved 7 July 2010.</ref>\n\nAfter ''The Horns'' broke up in the late 1970s both Thoms and Ferari joined ex-[[Hawkwind]]'s [[Nik Turner]] in [[Inner City Unit]]. Thoms also worked with Turner and [[Twink (musician)|Twink]] under the hybrid [[Pink Fairies]]/[[Hawkwind]] name '''Pink Wind'''. He later formed [[Atomgods]] and has worked with other ex-Hawkwind members including [[Ron Tree]].<ref>Aural Innovations, [http://www.aural-innovations.com/issues/issue30/moab01.html The Mother Of All Bands - \"Insect Brain\"], Retrieved 7 July 2010.</ref> He and Ferari formed their own version of Inner City Unit called '''Judge Trev's Inner City Unit'''.  A regular 'collaborator' he also played with the revived Pinkwind featuring [[Nik Turner]] & [[Twink (musician)|Twink]] (ex [[Pink Fairies]]) and after moving to Brighton regularly appeared with Slim Tim Slide (Tim Rundall) sometimes under the pseudonym \"Stinky & Stumpy\", a partnership that continued sporadically for the rest of Thoms' life.\n\nHe played festivals such as the [[Big Green Gathering]], [[Cosmic Puffin Festival]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cosmicpuffin.co.uk |title=Page Title |publisher=Cosmicpuffin.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref> [[Glastonbury Festival|Glastonbury]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.realfestivalmusic.co.uk/glasto2007.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070812023115/http://www.realfestivalmusic.co.uk/glasto2007.html |archivedate=2007-08-12 |title=GLASTONBURY FESTIVAL 2007}}</ref> Earthwise etc., performing his solo acoustic set or with the reformed Inner City Unit with Nik Turner. He also played gigs as [[Trev and Kev]] with [[Kev Ellis]], singer from [[Bubbledubble]].\n\nHe also ran the website Real Festival Music<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realfestivalmusic.co.uk/ |title=Music Store |publisher=Realfestivalmusic.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref> where he also wrote festival reviews.\n\nThoms died on 8 December 2010 from [[pancreatic cancer]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.nikturner.com/ |title=The Mighty Thunder Rider |publisher=Nik Turner |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref>\n\nDuring the last years of Trevs life he was active in forming The Real Music Club in Brighton and indeed his last ever gig was at a RMC event to celebrate his birthday, and his last recordings were with fellow RMC members Paradise 9. With the aim of promoting local talent as well as providing an outlet for his own work the club continues both live and on Brighton and Hove Community radio www.bhcr.org.uk and annual Trev Memorial gigs are ongoing.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Archive of Official website (defunct since his death) https://web.archive.org/web/20110912184351/http://www.judgetrev.com/\n* [{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p131504|pure_url=yes}} Trev Thomas] at [[allmusic]]\n* [{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p571273|pure_url=yes}} Judge Trev Thoms] at [[allmusic]]\n* {{Discogs artist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thoms, Trev}}\n[[Category:British guitarists]]\n[[Category:British male guitarists]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n'''Trevor Thoms'''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/announcements/deaths/deaths/8735913.Judge_Trev/|title=Death Notices and Obituaries: Judge Trev|last=|first=|date=14 December 2010|work=The Brighton Argus|access-date=15 August 2019}}</ref> (30 October 1950 \u2013 8 December 2010),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metal-archives.com/artists/Judge_Trev_Thoms/19263|title=Judge Trev Thoms|last=|first=|date=11 April 2011|website=Encyclopaedia Metallum - The Metal Archives|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 August 2019}}</ref> known as '''Judge Trev Thoms''' and '''Judge Trev''', was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[guitarist]], best known for being a member of [[Inner City Unit]], [[Atomgods]] and [[Steve Gibbons (musician)#Steve Gibbons Band|The Steve Gibbons Band]].\n\nIn the late 1960s and early 1970s, he played in a [[blues-rock]] group with hints of [[progressive rock]] and [[Hard rock|heavy rock]] called [[Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Iron Maiden (blues rock band)|Iron Maiden]] - not the [[Iron Maiden|famous group]] of the same name - along with Barry Skeels,<ref>Skeels, Barry (1998). Notes to CD reissue of ''Maiden Voyage''. London: Audio Archives AACD 028.</ref> who later played for Zior<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spirit-of-metal.com/groupe-groupe-Zior-l-pt.html |title=Zior - discografia, line-up, biografia, entrevistas, fotos |publisher=Spirit-of-metal.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/zior-mn0000911850 |title=Zior &#124; Discography |publisher=AllMusic |date=2005-01-04 |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref> and eventually became a [[tour manager]] for acts such as [[Black Sabbath]], [[Saxon (band)|Saxon]], [[Manowar]], and [[Yngwie Malmsteen]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livebluesworld.com/profile/BarrySkeels |title=Barry Skeels's Page |publisher=LiveBluesWorld |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref> (another member of the band was called Steve Drewett, but probably he is not the same person as the one who later founded [[The Newtown Neurotics]]).<ref>Progboard, [http://www.progboard.com/Iron-Maiden/604# Iron Maiden], Retrieved 7 July 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trouserpress.com/entry.php?a=newtown_neurotics |title=Newtown Neurotics |publisher=TrouserPress.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/steve-drewett-mn0000034324 |title=Steve Drewett &#124; Songs |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref> They recorded one album called ''Maiden Voyage''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/iron_maiden_2_/albums.jhtml?albumId=1435904 |title=Maiden Voyage by Iron Maiden |publisher=MTV |date=1969-01-01 |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/maiden-voyage-mw0000461150 |title=Maiden Voyage - Iron Maiden &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref>\n\nHe later played in the seminal British Blues Boom band, [[Spirit of John Morgan]].<ref>Brennan, Mark (1993). Notes to CD reissue of ''Spirit of John Morgan - Age Machine''. [[Repertoire Records]] REP 4354-WP.</ref> He has backed such luminaries as [[Graham Bond]], [[Gregory Isaacs]], [[Steve Gibbons (musician)|Steve Gibbons]] and was a member of [[Steve Peregrin Took]]'s  band [[Steve Took's Horns]] with [[Dino Ferari]] on [[Drum kit|drums]].<ref>Steve Peregrin Took's Domain, [http://www.stevetook.mercurymoon.co.uk/horns.html Steve Took's Horns], Retrieved 7 July 2010.</ref>\n\nAfter ''The Horns'' broke up in the late 1970s both Thoms and Ferari joined ex-[[Hawkwind]]'s [[Nik Turner]] in [[Inner City Unit]]. Thoms also worked with Turner and [[Twink (musician)|Twink]] under the hybrid [[Pink Fairies]]/[[Hawkwind]] name '''Pink Wind'''. He later formed [[Atomgods]] and has worked with other ex-Hawkwind members including [[Ron Tree]].<ref>Aural Innovations, [http://www.aural-innovations.com/issues/issue30/moab01.html The Mother Of All Bands - \"Insect Brain\"], Retrieved 7 July 2010.</ref> He and Ferari formed their own version of Inner City Unit called '''Judge Trev's Inner City Unit'''.  A regular 'collaborator' he also played with the revived Pinkwind featuring [[Nik Turner]] & [[Twink (musician)|Twink]] (ex [[Pink Fairies]]) and after moving to Brighton regularly appeared with Slim Tim Slide (Tim Rundall) sometimes under the pseudonym \"Stinky & Stumpy\", a partnership that continued sporadically for the rest of Thoms' life.\n\nHe played festivals such as the [[Big Green Gathering]], [[Cosmic Puffin Festival]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cosmicpuffin.co.uk |title=Page Title |publisher=Cosmicpuffin.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref> [[Glastonbury Festival|Glastonbury]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.realfestivalmusic.co.uk/glasto2007.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070812023115/http://www.realfestivalmusic.co.uk/glasto2007.html |archivedate=2007-08-12 |title=GLASTONBURY FESTIVAL 2007}}</ref> Earthwise etc., performing his solo acoustic set or with the reformed Inner City Unit with Nik Turner. He also played gigs as [[Trev and Kev]] with [[Kev Ellis]], singer from [[Bubbledubble]].\n\nHe also ran the website Real Festival Music<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realfestivalmusic.co.uk/ |title=Music Store |publisher=Realfestivalmusic.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref> where he also wrote festival reviews.\n\nThoms died on 8 December 2010 from [[pancreatic cancer]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.nikturner.com/ |title=The Mighty Thunder Rider |publisher=Nik Turner |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref>\n\nDuring the last years of Trevs life he was active in forming The Real Music Club in Brighton and indeed his last ever gig was at a RMC event to celebrate his birthday, and his last recordings were with fellow RMC members Paradise 9. With the aim of promoting local talent as well as providing an outlet for his own work the club continues both live and on Brighton and Hove Community radio www.bhcr.org.uk and annual Trev Memorial gigs are ongoing.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Archive of Official website (defunct since his death) https://web.archive.org/web/20110912184351/http://www.judgetrev.com/\n* [{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p131504|pure_url=yes}} Trev Thomas] at [[allmusic]]\n* [{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p571273|pure_url=yes}} Judge Trev Thoms] at [[allmusic]]\n* {{Discogs artist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thoms, Trev}}\n[[Category:British guitarists]]\n[[Category:British male guitarists]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trev_Thoms"}
